    {
      "title": "Sound Masculine Plural (جمع المذكر السالم)",
      "titleArabic": "جمع المذكر السالم",
      "content": [
        "The sound masculine plural (جمع المذكر السالم) is formed by adding ون (nominative) or ين (accusative/genitive) to masculine nouns referring to rational beings.",
        "This plural is called 'sound' because the original word remains intact (the letters are preserved)."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Nominative (مرفوع): ـونَ (e.g., مُعَلِّمُونَ)",
        "Accusative/Genitive (منصوب/مجرور): ـينَ (e.g., مُعَلِّمِينَ)",
        "Only for masculine, rational beings",
        "The original noun's ending (tanwīn or ة) is removed before adding the suffix",
        "Numbers 20-90 (العقود) follow the same pattern"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "جَاءَ الْمُعَلِّمُونَ", "english": "The teachers came (nominative)" },
        { "arabic": "رَأَيْتُ الْمُهَنْدِسِينَ", "english": "I saw the engineers (accusative)" },
        { "arabic": "سَلَّمْتُ عَلَى الْمُسْلِمِينَ", "english": "I greeted the Muslims (genitive)" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Numbers 20-90 as Sound Masculine Plural",
      "titleArabic": "العقود كجمع المذكر السالم",
      "content": [
        "The tens (عِشْرُونَ، ثَلَاثُونَ، etc.) follow the sound masculine plural pattern in their declension."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Nominative: عِشْرُونَ، ثَلَاثُونَ، أَرْبَعُونَ",
        "Accusative/Genitive: عِشْرِينَ، ثَلَاثِينَ، أَرْبَعِينَ",
        "عِشْرُونَ طَالِبًا (twenty students - nominative)",
        "رَأَيْتُ عِشْرِينَ طَالِبًا (I saw twenty students - accusative)"
      ]
    }
  ],
